  "prompt": "I am repairing a soft steel chair by arc welding and keep burning holes in the metal, what can I do to make a strong joint?",
  "response": "Here are some tips to help you arc weld soft steel without burning holes:\n\n1. Lower welding current\n- Use a lower amperage setting\n- Match current to metal thickness\n\n2. Use proper technique\n- Keep electrode at correct angle\n- Move electrode steadily\n- Maintain consistent arc length\n- Use shorter, quicker passes\n\n3. Choose correct electrode\n- Use thinner electrodes for thin metal\n- Select low-hydrogen electrodes\n- Choose 6013 or 7014 for thin steel\n\n4. Practice beforehand\n- Use scrap metal to practice technique\n- Adjust settings and speed\n\n5. Preheat metal if very thin\n- Reduces thermal shock\n- Helps prevent burn-through\n\n6. Use tack welds first\n- Small spot welds to hold pieces\n- Helps distribute heat\n\n7. Consider alternative methods\n- TIG welding for thin metal\n- MIG welding with lower heat\n\nRemember to wear proper safety gear and work in a well-ventilated area.",
